\ls4\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}What does the rolling average do to our data?\
\pard\tx720\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 The rolling average smooths out our short-term year to year noise in the graph, making the long term increasing trend easier to see. Individual years can spike up or down due to certain events, but the moving average filters that out.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls5\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}Which decade (70s, 80s, 90s, 2000s, 2010s) saw the largest jump in average temperature, when compared to the average temperature of the previous decade?\
\pard\tx720\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 The 2000s saw the largest jump compared to the 90s.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls6\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}What other trends do you observe?\
\pard\tx720\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 One trend I\'92m noticing is that the most recent years show a massive spike well above the 2010s trend showing further upwards acceleration. Another trend I see is that the 1960s and 1970s were relatively flat compared to the following decades showing the temperatures were close to the 1951-1980 baseline.\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
